<subSubSection id="59F4654C560B6948C8DC02F28002F889" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="115136C7560B6948C8DC02F28002F889" blockId="4.[151,1437,1482,1942]" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">
<emphasis id="239AEAD5560B6948C8DC02F28253F984" bold="true" box="[199,324,1518,1544]" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
Externally, 
<taxonomicName id="D6EE4D44560B6948C9D402F3816AF985" authorityName="Li" authorityYear="2016" box="[463,637,1519,1545]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Teliphasa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="similalbifusa">
<emphasis id="239AEAD5560B6948C9D402F3816AF985" box="[463,637,1519,1545]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">T. similalbifusa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="89D52A42560B6948CA9402F381F6F985" box="[655,737,1519,1545]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–10" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1198,1222]" captionTargetBox="[168,1413,193,1164]" captionTargetId="figure-29@3.[151,1435,181,1175]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 7–10. Imago of Teliphasa spp. 7, male &amp; 8, female, T. spinaejuxta sp. nov; 9, male, T. erythrina; 10, male, T. similalbifusa." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6577736" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6577736/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
) is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="D6EE4D44560B6948CB9802F380E3F985" authorityName="Li" authorityYear="2016" box="[899,1012,1519,1545]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Teliphasa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hamata">
<emphasis id="239AEAD5560B6948CB9802F380E3F985" box="[899,1012,1519,1545]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">T. hamata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="89D52A42560B6948CC1D02F3877BF985" box="[1030,1132,1519,1545]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1829,1853]" captionTargetBox="[164,1416,193,1790]" captionTargetId="figure-19@2.[151,1436,179,1803]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Imago of Teliphasa spp. 1, male &amp; 2, female, T. nubilosa; 3, male &amp; 4, female, T. hamata; 5, male, holotype &amp; 6, male, paratype, T. dodaki sp. nov.;" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6577734" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6577734/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">Figs 3, 4</figureCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName id="D6EE4D44560B6948CCB502F38636F984" authorityName="Li" authorityYear="2016" box="[1198,1313,1519,1544]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Teliphasa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinosa">
<emphasis id="239AEAD5560B6948CCB502F38636F984" box="[1198,1313,1519,1544]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">T. spinosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="757F4B36560B6948CD2A02F383C4F9A1" author="Liu, L. &amp; Wang, Y. &amp; Li, H." pageId="4" pageNumber="64" pagination="119 - 137" refId="ref5167" refString="Liu, L., Wang, Y. &amp; Li, H. (2016) Taxonomic review of the genus Teliphasa Moore, 1888 from China, with descriptions of four new species (Lepidoptera, Pyralidae, Epipaschiinae). ZooKeys, 554, 119 - 137. https: // doi. org / 10.3897 / zookeys. 554.6177" type="journal article" year="2016">
Liu 
<emphasis id="239AEAD5560B6948CD7902F38682F985" box="[1378,1429,1519,1545]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">et al</emphasis>
. 2016
</bibRefCitation>
: 
<figureCitation id="89D52A42560B6948C8C4010F8235F9A1" box="[223,290,1554,1581]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1829,1853]" captionTargetBox="[164,1416,193,1790]" captionTargetId="figure-19@2.[151,1436,179,1803]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Imago of Teliphasa spp. 1, male &amp; 2, female, T. nubilosa; 3, male &amp; 4, female, T. hamata; 5, male, holotype &amp; 6, male, paratype, T. dodaki sp. nov.;" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6577734" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6577734/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
), but is clearly distinct from 
<taxonomicName id="D6EE4D44560B6948CA77010F81CAF9A1" authorityName="Li" authorityYear="2016" box="[620,733,1555,1581]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Teliphasa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hamata">
<emphasis id="239AEAD5560B6948CA77010F81CAF9A1" box="[620,733,1555,1581]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">T. hamata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the forewing’s broader postmedial line at the costa, as well as in the male genitalia (
<figureCitation id="89D52A42560B6948C9B3012B82EFF9DD" box="[424,504,1591,1617]" captionStart="FIGURES 14–19" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[269,1315,198,1909]" captionTargetId="figure-19@6.[247,1340,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 14–19. Male genitalia of Teliphasa spp. 14, T. erythrina; 15, T. nubilosa; 16, T. dodaki sp. nov.; 17, T. similalbifusa; 18, T. hamata; 19, T. spinaejuxta sp. nov.." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6577740" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6577740/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
) with the juxta having a short, robust and sclerotised process, whereas in 
<taxonomicName id="D6EE4D44560B6948CD36012B868BF9DD" authorityName="Li" authorityYear="2016" box="[1325,1436,1591,1617]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Teliphasa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hamata">
<emphasis id="239AEAD5560B6948CD36012B868BF9DD" box="[1325,1436,1591,1617]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">T. hamata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the juxtal process (
<figureCitation id="89D52A42560B6948C96A014782D4F9F9" box="[369,451,1627,1653]" captionStart="FIGURES 14–19" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[269,1315,198,1909]" captionTargetId="figure-19@6.[247,1340,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 14–19. Male genitalia of Teliphasa spp. 14, T. erythrina; 15, T. nubilosa; 16, T. dodaki sp. nov.; 17, T. similalbifusa; 18, T. hamata; 19, T. spinaejuxta sp. nov.." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6577740" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6577740/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
) is elongate, thin and bent medially. 
<taxonomicName id="D6EE4D44560B6948CB7501478763F9F9" authorityName="Li" authorityYear="2016" box="[878,1140,1627,1653]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Teliphasa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="similalbifusa">
<emphasis id="239AEAD5560B6948CB7501478763F9F9" box="[878,1140,1627,1653]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">Teliphasa similalbifusa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is further distinct from 
<taxonomicName id="D6EE4D44560B6948CD93014783FAF914" authorityName="Li" authorityYear="2016" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Teliphasa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinosa">
<emphasis id="239AEAD5560B6948CD93014783FAF914" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">T. spinosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the forewing marginal band bent medially, and in the male genitalia by the almost circular valva and the single robust, elongate juxta spine, whereas in 
<taxonomicName id="D6EE4D44560B6948CAB301BF800DF930" authorityName="Li" authorityYear="2016" box="[680,794,1699,1724]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Teliphasa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinosa">
<emphasis id="239AEAD5560B6948CAB301BF800DF930" box="[680,794,1699,1724]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">T. spinosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the marginal band of the forewing is almost rectangular (
<bibRefCitation id="757F4B36560B6948C88401DB825AF96D" author="Liu, L. &amp; Wang, Y. &amp; Li, H." box="[159,333,1735,1761]" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" pagination="119 - 137" refId="ref5167" refString="Liu, L., Wang, Y. &amp; Li, H. (2016) Taxonomic review of the genus Teliphasa Moore, 1888 from China, with descriptions of four new species (Lepidoptera, Pyralidae, Epipaschiinae). ZooKeys, 554, 119 - 137. https: // doi. org / 10.3897 / zookeys. 554.6177" type="journal article" year="2016">
Liu 
<emphasis id="239AEAD5560B6948C8CB01DB8215F96D" box="[208,258,1735,1761]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">et al</emphasis>
. 2016
</bibRefCitation>
: 
<figureCitation id="89D52A42560B6948C94201DB828AF96D" box="[345,413,1734,1761]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1829,1853]" captionTargetBox="[164,1416,193,1790]" captionTargetId="figure-19@2.[151,1436,179,1803]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Imago of Teliphasa spp. 1, male &amp; 2, female, T. nubilosa; 3, male &amp; 4, female, T. hamata; 5, male, holotype &amp; 6, male, paratype, T. dodaki sp. nov.;" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6577734" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6577734/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
), and in male genitalia the juxta is a broad plate like with a central longitudinal cluster of small spines (
<bibRefCitation id="757F4B36560B6948C92B01F782CDF889" author="Liu, L. &amp; Wang, Y. &amp; Li, H." box="[304,474,1771,1797]" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" pagination="119 - 137" refId="ref5167" refString="Liu, L., Wang, Y. &amp; Li, H. (2016) Taxonomic review of the genus Teliphasa Moore, 1888 from China, with descriptions of four new species (Lepidoptera, Pyralidae, Epipaschiinae). ZooKeys, 554, 119 - 137. https: // doi. org / 10.3897 / zookeys. 554.6177" type="journal article" year="2016">
Liu 
<emphasis id="239AEAD5560B6948C94401F78287F889" box="[351,400,1771,1797]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">et al</emphasis>
. 2016
</bibRefCitation>
: 
<figureCitation id="89D52A42560B6948C9FE01F78120F889" box="[485,567,1771,1797]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–13" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1347,1371]" captionTargetBox="[174,1413,193,1313]" captionTargetId="figure-29@5.[159,1428,181,1323]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 11–13. Female genitalia of Teliphasa spp. 11, T. nubilosa; 12, T. hamata; 13, T. spinaejuxta sp. nov." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6577738" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6577738/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
). Female unknown.
</paragraph>
